    In establishing proper referential relations, we found the functional information structure of the utterances to be much more relevant.
    By this we mean indicators of whether or not a discourse entity in the current utterance refers to another discourse entity already introduced by previous utterances in the discourse.
    Borrowing terminology from Prince (1981, 1992), an entity that does refer to another discourse entity already introduced is called discourse-old or hearer-old, while an entity that does not refer to another discourse entity is called discourse-new or hearer-new.
    Based on evidence from empirical studies in which we considered German as well as English texts from different domains and genres, we make three contributions to the centering approach.
